title: For Sale:  Fightin Rifle Course
postcontent:
Overview:You've got the rifle; now learn how to use it! A great deal of people who own sporting type rifles are not fully aware of the rifles potential uses; but don't worry, we've got you covered. In this course, you will be properly trained on how to use your fighting rifle in austere environments. This includes a multitude of combat drills as well as shooting on the move. This course also serves as a measuring device as to how much gear you can handle while shooting. Students are encouraged to bring the entirety of their kit, but if you wish to wear normal clothes you are more than welcome.
 
Gear List:1. An open mind2. A fighting rifle or carbine- Pistol caliber rifles and rifle caliber pistols are ok3. Six (6) magazines for your rifle or carbine4. 500 rounds minimum for your rifle or carbine (the more the merrier)5. A fighting Pistol (no single action revolvers)6. Three (3) magazines for your pistol7. 250 rounds minimum for your pistol (the more the merrier)8. A holster for your pistol9. A tactical sling for your rifle or carbine10. Ear and Eye protection (muffs preferred)11. A sack lunch12. Proper clothing13. A water source (camelback recommended)14. Gloves (mechanix gloves work well)
 
Recommended Gear:Pouches for rifle or carbine magazinesPouches for pistol magazinesElbow and knee pads
 
Location:Miami Valley Shooting Grounds7771 Johnson Station RoadVandalia OH, 45377
 
Date and Time:May 27th 201610am to 6pm
 
Contact Information:phone: REDACTED
 
Instructor Bio:The head instructor for the course is retired Infantry Marine Christopher May. Christopher May served in multiple combat deployments with 2nd Battalion 6th Marines during his service. His combat experiences span from the violent streets of Fallujah, Iraq; to the Al-qaeda stronghold in Marjah, Afghanistan during Operation: Moshtarak. Mr. May has a very strong infantry combat background as he was a squad leader during Operation: Moshtarak and was tasked with controlling key parts of the city, training the soldiers of the Afghanistan National Army and Afghanistan National Police, as well as fighting against a well-trained enemy in their own back yard. His expertise in this area gives him the ability to easily translate and teach his skills to a wide range of people. Any assistant instructors that may be used are hand selected by Chris May and will have an equal combat background.
 
Additional Information:- A discount is offered if more than one person is signing up at a time in a group. Call for details- There are no specific types of ammunition recommended or required, just make sure it functions well in your weapons.- You are more than welcome to wear as much tactical gear/ clothing as you wish, but please do not over encumber yourself. You will be moving and shooting and too much weight can potentially hurt you- Once you arrive at the range, you WILL be required to sign a liability waiver before you shoot- No waiver= No shooting- Water and snacks will be provided at the range- If you have any questions or concerns about the course, please call the Ohio Warfare Institute directly at REDACTED
 
Thanks for your participation and we look forward to working with you!

title: For Sale:  S&W K200
postcontent:
A .38 S&W K200 Victory model revolver. This is the forerunner to the .38 special we know today. This particular revolver is a .38/200 British Service Revolver made by Smith and Wesson in the USA. It has a 5 inch pinned barrel and was made somewhere around 1943. Most of these revolvers went to England around this time but there are no proof marks on this to suggest a military or export model. It has the original grips. It does not have the "V" serial number prefix or the "US Property" mark meaning it was most likely a civilian model. I never lettered it from Smith and Wesson to find out any details since it was bound to be a restoration piece for me. This gun was never converted to .38 special after the war like a lot were and is chambered for the .38 S&W (short .38). According to experts the serial number puts it in the range of the later hardened steel cylinders so if you decided to shoot this beauty it can take modern .38 S&W ammo, NOT .38 Special though!
 
Looking for trades also, let me know what you have, worst I can say is no.
